};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best form of zinc in gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zinc bisglycinate (chelated with glycine) offers the best absorption and lowest GI side effect risk. Zinc citrate and zinc gluconate are also well-absorbed and widely used in gummy formulations. Zinc oxide has the poorest absorption at approximately 50% of zinc citrate levels and is more likely to cause nausea. A 2014 study in the Journal of the American College of Nutrition found that zinc bisglycinate was 43% better absorbed than zinc gluconate in healthy adults. For gummies specifically, zinc citrate and gluconate are the most common forms due to their compatible taste profile and adequate bioavailability.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much zinc should I take daily?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Recommended Dietary Allowance for zinc is 8mg per day for adult women and 11mg per day for adult men. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 40mg per day for adults, above which copper deficiency can develop over time because zinc and copper compete for the same absorption pathway (metallothionein). Most zinc gummies provide 11 to 30mg per serving. A daily supplement of 15mg is generally appropriate for most adults, as it accounts for the approximately 5 to 8mg typically obtained from food. Exceeding 40mg daily without medical supervision is not recommended.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can zinc gummies help prevent colds?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'A 2017 Cochrane review analyzing 18 randomized controlled trials found that zinc supplementation within 24 hours of cold symptom onset significantly reduced cold duration by an average of 1 to 2 days and reduced symptom severity. However, the evidence for zinc as a preventive measure (taken daily before symptoms appear) is less consistent. A 2021 meta-analysis in BMJ Open found that prophylactic zinc supplementation reduced the incidence of respiratory tract infections by approximately 28% in adults with adequate study durations. The key is consistent daily supplementation rather than acute dosing after symptoms begin.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can you take too much zinc?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, excessive zinc intake can cause both acute and chronic adverse effects. Acute symptoms from single doses above 40mg include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and metallic taste. Chronic excessive intake (above 40mg daily for extended periods) can lead to copper deficiency because zinc induces the production of metallothionein in intestinal cells, which preferentially binds copper and prevents its absorption. Copper deficiency manifests as anemia, neutropenia (low white blood cells), and neurological symptoms that can mimic B12 deficiency. Always stay below 40mg total daily zinc from all sources.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take zinc gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zinc gummies are best taken with a meal to minimize the nausea that can occur with zinc on an empty stomach. Taking zinc with food also improves absorption when protein and amino acids are present, as they facilitate zinc transport across the intestinal wall. Avoid taking zinc at the same time as calcium, iron, or copper supplements, as these minerals compete for the same absorption pathways. If you also take a multivitamin containing these minerals, separate your zinc gummy by at least 2 hours. Morning or evening dosing is equally effective — consistency matters more than timing.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Does zinc help with skin and acne?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zinc plays a critical role in skin health through multiple mechanisms: it regulates sebum production, supports wound healing, modulates inflammatory cytokines, and is required for protein synthesis and cell division in skin tissue. A 2020 systematic review in Dermatologic Therapy analyzed 12 studies and found that oral zinc supplementation (30 to 45mg daily) significantly reduced inflammatory acne lesions compared to placebo. Zinc also supports the skin barrier function by maintaining metallothionein levels that protect against UV damage and oxidative stress. For acne specifically, zinc gluconate at 30mg daily for 3 months is the most studied protocol.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Who is most at risk for zinc deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zinc deficiency affects an estimated 17% of the global population, though severe deficiency is uncommon in the United States. The highest-risk groups include vegetarians and vegans (plant-based diets contain phytates that inhibit zinc absorption by up to 50%), pregnant and lactating women (increased zinc requirements), adults over 65 (reduced absorption and lower dietary intake), individuals with gastrointestinal conditions (Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis, celiac disease), and people who consume excessive alcohol (alcohol reduces zinc absorption and increases urinary zinc excretion). Athletes who sweat heavily may also have elevated zinc losses.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take zinc and vitamin C together?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, zinc and vitamin C can be taken together safely and may provide complementary immune benefits. Vitamin C does not significantly affect zinc absorption, and there are no known adverse interactions between the two nutrients. Many immunity-focused supplements combine zinc with vitamin C for this reason. A 2012 Cochrane review found that both zinc and vitamin C independently reduced cold duration, and some researchers hypothesize an additive effect, though direct comparison studies are limited. Taking both nutrients during cold and flu season is a common and evidence-supported strategy.' },
    },
  ],
};
