    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Zinc Forms Compared: Absorption, Side Effects, and Best Uses</h4>
      <p>The form of zinc in your gummy determines how efficiently it is absorbed and whether you experience the nausea and metallic taste that zinc supplements are notorious for causing. Understanding these differences is essential for choosing the right product.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Zinc Bisglycinate</strong>
          <p>Absorption: Highest (43% better than gluconate). Chelated with glycine, absorbed through amino acid transporters. Minimal GI side effects. Best for sensitive stomachs and maximum bioavailability. Found in Mary Ruth's and NOW Foods.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Zinc Citrate</strong>
          <p>Absorption: Good (comparable to gluconate). Well-tolerated at standard doses. The most common form in gummies due to favorable taste profile. Moderate GI risk at higher doses. Found in Nature Made, Vitafusion, and Nature's Bounty.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Zinc Gluconate</strong>
          <p>Absorption: Good. The most clinically studied form for cold prevention and treatment. Used in the majority of Cochrane-reviewed clinical trials. Widely available and well-characterized. Found in Zicam.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Zinc Oxide</strong>
          <p>Absorption: Poor (approximately 50% of citrate). The cheapest form but least bioavailable. Higher risk of nausea and metallic taste. Used primarily in low-cost tablets. Not recommended for gummies where better options exist.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Practical dosing guide:</strong> The adult RDA is 8mg for women and 11mg for men. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 40mg from all sources (food + supplements). A 15mg zinc gummy combined with a typical diet (9-13mg from food) brings total intake to 24-28mg — well within the safe range and sufficient for immune support. Avoid exceeding 40mg total daily zinc to prevent copper depletion.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Zinc-copper interaction:</strong> Chronic zinc intake above 40mg per day induces excessive metallothionein production in intestinal cells, which binds copper and prevents its absorption. Copper deficiency causes anemia (indistinguishable from iron deficiency on basic blood work), neutropenia (increased infection risk), and potentially irreversible neurological damage. If you take a high-dose zinc supplement (25mg+), consider also taking 1-2mg of supplemental copper, separated by 2 hours, to prevent depletion.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

