    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Zinc Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best form of zinc in gummies?</summary>
      <p>Zinc bisglycinate offers the best absorption (43% better than gluconate in published research) and the lowest risk of GI side effects. Zinc citrate and gluconate are also well-absorbed and widely used. Zinc oxide has the poorest absorption at approximately 50% of citrate levels. For gummies specifically, citrate and gluconate are the most common forms due to their compatible taste profile. If you have a sensitive stomach, bisglycinate is the clear choice.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much zinc should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 8mg for women and 11mg for men. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 40mg daily from all sources. Most zinc gummies provide 15-25mg per serving. A 15mg supplement combined with dietary zinc (9-13mg from food) brings total intake to 24-28mg — well within the safe range. Exceeding 40mg daily without medical supervision increases the risk of copper depletion over time due to competitive absorption pathways.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can zinc gummies help prevent colds?</summary>
      <p>A 2021 meta-analysis in <em>BMJ Open</em> found that prophylactic zinc supplementation reduced respiratory tract infection incidence by 28% and shortened duration by 2.25 days. The evidence is strongest for consistent daily supplementation at 15-30mg, rather than acute megadosing after symptoms begin. A 2017 Cochrane review confirmed that zinc started within 24 hours of cold onset significantly reduced cold duration by approximately 33%.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can you take too much zinc?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Acute symptoms from doses above 40mg include nausea, vomiting, and metallic taste. Chronic excessive intake leads to copper deficiency because zinc induces metallothionein that binds copper and prevents its absorption. Copper deficiency manifests as anemia, neutropenia, and neurological symptoms. Stay below 40mg total daily zinc from all sources (food + supplements) unless directed by a physician.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take zinc gummies?</summary>
      <p>Take zinc gummies with a meal to minimize nausea and improve absorption. Protein-containing foods facilitate zinc transport across the intestinal wall. Avoid taking zinc at the same time as calcium, iron, or copper supplements — separate by at least 2 hours. Morning or evening dosing is equally effective; consistency matters more than timing for maintaining optimal zinc status.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does zinc help with skin and acne?</summary>
      <p>Zinc regulates sebum production, supports wound healing, and modulates inflammatory cytokines in the skin. A 2020 systematic review in <em>Dermatologic Therapy</em> found that oral zinc at 30-45mg daily significantly reduced inflammatory acne lesions. Zinc gluconate at 30mg daily for 3 months is the most studied protocol. Zinc also supports the skin barrier through metallothionein that protects against UV damage and oxidative stress.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Who is most at risk for zinc deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Highest-risk groups include vegetarians and vegans (phytates in plants inhibit zinc absorption by up to 50%), adults over 65 (reduced absorption and intake), pregnant and lactating women (increased requirements), individuals with GI conditions (Crohn, celiac, post-bariatric surgery), and heavy alcohol consumers (alcohol reduces zinc absorption and increases urinary excretion). Athletes with heavy sweat losses may also need additional zinc.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take zinc and vitamin C together?</summary>
      <p>Yes, zinc and vitamin C can be taken together safely with no known adverse interactions. Vitamin C does not significantly affect zinc absorption, and both nutrients independently support immune function. Many immunity-focused supplements combine both nutrients for this reason. Taking both during cold and flu season is a common and evidence-supported strategy for reducing infection risk and duration.</p>
    </details>

